00:26:51.156 --> 00:26:54.896
or is it a non-mediated decay type of transcript?

463
00:26:55.396 --> 00:26:56.656
Is it regulated as needed?

464
00:26:57.196 --> 00:27:00.266
Yes. Fantastic question. So the question is,

465
00:27:01.356 --> 00:27:04.816
what is the mechanism behind how detained introns

466
00:27:04.856 --> 00:27:08.016
affect gene expression? And

467
00:27:08.716 --> 00:27:11.596
the answer to that is actually both of the

468
00:27:12.736 --> 00:27:16.316
descriptions you gave are true in different cases.

469
00:27:16.396 --> 00:27:18.366
So in some cases,

470
00:27:19.536 --> 00:27:21.616
these detained introns can

471
00:27:23.516 --> 00:27:27.476
form a sort of a pool of RNAs that are

472
00:27:27.536 --> 00:27:30.716
mostly spliced but may be lacking one intron.

473
00:27:30.756 --> 00:27:31.536
They're ready to go,

474
00:27:32.376 --> 00:27:36.316
and these can actually be triggered to undergo full

475
00:27:36.456 --> 00:27:38.816
