00:45:01.280 --> 00:45:04.580
RNA away from the decay complex in the cytoplasm.

781
00:45:05.340 --> 00:45:09.260
To test this, we did base scope, which is a really sensitive RNA FISH technique

782
00:45:09.660 --> 00:45:13.540
in the control and Z18 lines. And what you can see here, the blue is the

783
00:45:13.560 --> 00:45:17.420
DAPI marking the nucleus, and then you can see here that the red really

784
00:45:17.480 --> 00:45:20.900
shows up in the cytoplasm, so the ERV RNA is accumulating in the

785
00:45:20.920 --> 00:45:22.740
cytoplasm, quantified here.

786
00:45:25.040 --> 00:45:28.940
So that supported Model 1, and so we

787
00:45:28.960 --> 00:45:32.560
were wondering if the Z18 actually was directly binding the ERV RNA.

788
00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:36.000
And so to think about how this could be working, we looked at the

789
00:45:36.060 --> 00:45:39.920
conservation of Z18, and the two major domains that are really

790
00:45:39.940 --> 00:45:42.970
conserved are the RNA surveillance binding domain, which I already told you about,

791
00:45:43.540 --> 00:45:46.460
and then this CCCH zinc finger domain.

792
00:45:46.520 --> 00:45:50.240
So this is actually what the Z18 protein is named for, ZC3H,

793
00:45:50.940 --> 00:45:54.820
and so we looked at this. Now, there's no crystal structure for Z18 yet,

794
00:45:55.420 --> 00:45:57.540
so we modeled this on an existing

795
00:45:57.640 --> 00:46:00.740
CCCH domain protein called

796
00:46:00.800 --> 00:46:04.770
RBM22 to kind of imagine how this could be interacting with RNA.

797
00:46:06.340 --> 00:46:09.800
So if you do this, the CCCH would

798
00:46:10.620 --> 00:46:12.260
bind with zinc, which makes total sense.

799
00:46:12.880 --> 00:46:16.360
But what's really cool is that there are a couple of, actually three, highly

800
00:46:16.400 --> 00:46:20.280
conserved aromatic amino acids which stick out from the zinc finger domain and are

801
00:46:20.300 --> 00:46:23.120
predicted to intercalate with RNA and directly bind RNA

802
00:46:24.699 --> 00:46:28.390
through pi-pi stacking. And so we wanted to test whether Z18 was

803
00:46:28.400 --> 00:46:31.680
directly binding ERV RNA by mutating these residues.

804
00:46:32.220 --> 00:46:34.280
To answer this question, we did a PAR-CLIP experiment.

805
00:46:34.320 --> 00:46:37.080
I'm not going to go into the details, but essentially what you do is pull down the

806
00:46:37.100 --> 00:46:39.060
protein and ask what RNAs come with it.

807
00:46:39.660 --> 00:46:43.300
And so what we did was did this for Z18 full length, the truncated

808
00:46:44.680 --> 00:46:48.600
version with an aromatic amino acid mutant, and then had a negative control.

809
00:46:49.460 --> 00:46:52.610
And what we found was the full length and the trunc bound a ton of different

810
00:46:52.640 --> 00:46:56.540
retroelement messages, whereas that binding was mostly abrogated

811
00:46:56.680 --> 00:46:58.040
in the aromatic zinc finger mutant.

812
00:47:00.420 --> 00:47:01.140
So lastly,

813
00:47:02.460 --> 00:47:05.880
the key thing, and this ended up being the key thing at the end of the CDK13 paper

814
00:47:05.920 --> 00:47:09.580
too, is we showed all this regulation by Z18 on these endogenous retroviral

815
00:47:09.680 --> 00:47:13.560
RNAs. But are those RNAs themselves responsible for the Z18

816
00:47:13.580 --> 00:47:16.960
phenotype? And so to answer this, we turned back to the zebrafish.

817
00:47:17.460 --> 00:47:21.260
And first, we took the BIC2 elements that were upregulated or stabilized in the

818
00:47:21.300 --> 00:47:24.950
fish and expressed them back into the animal model, and both of

819
00:47:25.020 --> 00:47:28.860
them expedited oncogenesis. As far as I'm aware, this is the first

820
00:47:28.920 --> 00:47:32.410
evidence that implicates ERV RNA as being functional in cancer.

821
00:47:33.060 --> 00:47:36.280
And also, it's pretty interesting because ERVs or LTRs are the most highly

822
00:47:36.320 --> 00:47:38.600
expressed repeat element in multiple types of cancer.

823
00:47:39.100 --> 00:47:41.360
And so maybe this is functional and not just a bystander.

824
00:47:42.400 --> 00:47:46.240
So next, we tried a crazy experiment. I had to convince my postdoc to do this.

825
00:47:46.620 --> 00:47:50.390
We took the two most highly Z18-regulated ERVs from human

826
00:47:50.480 --> 00:47:51.840
cells and then put them in the fish.

827
00:47:52.680 --> 00:47:56.540
And what was remarkable is that they actually expedited oncogenesis too.

828
00:47:57.200 --> 00:48:01.060
And so as this is a human ERV that's regulated by Z18 and the

829
00:48:01.080 --> 00:48:04.020
primary sequence is not conserved, it's very different between different

830
00:48:04.040 --> 00:48:08.000
species. However, it suggests a shared feature because Z18 is

831
00:48:08.020 --> 00:48:11.860
regulating them in both of these very different animals, and we're getting

832
00:48:11.900 --> 00:48:15.460
oncogenesis. So I think there's a shared underlying mechanism here

833
00:48:15.820 --> 00:48:19.788
of recognition that we're working on.So next, we wanted

834
00:48:19.948 --> 00:48:20.248
to

835
00:48:21.608 --> 00:48:25.368
test the necessity, because I showed you overexpression that can always

836
00:48:25.868 --> 00:48:29.838
come with caveats. And so to test the necessity in a zebrafish system, we had

837
00:48:29.848 --> 00:48:32.208
to create a CRISPR-I system, which we did.

838
00:48:32.288 --> 00:48:36.188
We adapted the system I explained earlier to inhibit

839
00:48:37.328 --> 00:48:41.108
for CRISPR-I. And here, as proof of concept, we inhibited a gene

840
00:48:41.148 --> 00:48:44.648
involved in pigmentation, and you can see the embryos on the right are less

841
00:48:44.668 --> 00:48:45.808
pigmented, so it worked.

842
00:48:47.528 --> 00:48:51.147
So next, we used this to answer the question of whether the ERV RNA itself

843
00:48:51.208 --> 00:48:53.908
was required for the Z18 phenotype.

844
00:48:54.228 --> 00:48:57.758
It does nothing in the GFP tumors, but in the Z18 tumors,

845
00:48:58.568 --> 00:49:02.088
in the dark blue there, it reverses the oncogenesis

846
00:49:02.588 --> 00:49:06.508
entirely. So it says that the Z18 phenotype was really due to

847
00:49:06.548 --> 00:49:07.378
the ERV RNA.

848
00:49:08.388 --> 00:49:12.128
We next did this in human cells, and remarkably, this experiment was actually hard

849
00:49:12.188 --> 00:49:14.988
to do because it killed all the cells.

850
00:49:15.048 --> 00:49:18.468
So CRISPR-I in the cells was a very

851
00:49:18.648 --> 00:49:19.778
effective killer.

852
00:49:21.308 --> 00:49:24.688
So to put all this together, Z18 mutations

853
00:49:25.048 --> 00:49:28.998
cause accumulation of endogenous retroviral RNA, and there's

854
00:49:29.028 --> 00:49:32.948
recurrent truncating mutations in this, and it's deleted in up to a third of

855
00:49:33.548 --> 00:49:35.608
all cancers, mostly epithelial cancers.

856
00:49:36.248 --> 00:49:39.728
Whether you're a patient that has this deleted, a cell line, or a zebrafish,

857
00:49:40.128 --> 00:49:42.308
there's an upregulation of ERV RNA.

858
00:49:43.288 --> 00:49:46.888
The truncating mutations work through a dominant negative mechanism and cause

859
00:49:46.928 --> 00:49:50.508
sequestration of the ERV RNA in the cytoplasm away from the decay

860
00:49:50.528 --> 00:49:54.068
machinery. And ERV RNA is necessary and sufficient for the

861
00:49:54.088 --> 00:49:56.588
Z18-driven melanomagenesis.

862
00:49:57.608 --> 00:50:00.828
You can see an earlier version of this manuscript in bioRxiv last year, and

863
00:50:00.868 --> 00:50:02.288
hopefully the full one will be out soon.

864
00:50:03.608 --> 00:50:05.068
Just a couple of discussion points.

865
00:50:05.488 --> 00:50:09.048
As far as I'm aware, this is the second genetic cause of ERV elevation in cancer.

866
00:50:09.108 --> 00:50:12.588
The first is loss of VHL in a beautiful paper by Zhang et al. earlier this year.

867
00:50:13.928 --> 00:50:17.768
ERV RNA as a driver could explain the high expression in cancer

868
00:50:17.788 --> 00:50:20.768
despite the known immunogenicity that is caused by ERVs.

869
00:50:21.868 --> 00:50:24.928
And it's interesting that there may be this RNA

870
00:50:26.068 --> 00:50:29.728
mechanism to work in concert with the DNA repression mechanisms to

871
00:50:29.748 --> 00:50:31.148
control these dangerous messages.

872
00:50:32.968 --> 00:50:36.848
So lastly, this is what I'm thinking about a lot, is how to

873
00:50:36.888 --> 00:50:40.808
target these things. And so I hope I've convinced you that RNAs can be drivers

874
00:50:40.828 --> 00:50:44.558
in cancer, and thus, because they can be drivers, they can be effective targets,

875
00:50:44.648 --> 00:50:48.288
either through targeting the complexes directly or maybe through targeting the

876
00:50:48.388 --> 00:50:50.408
RNAs. And this is ongoing work.

