1012
00:58:56.628 --> 00:59:00.548
And we decided to focus specifically in a very specific context, which

1013
00:59:00.588 --> 00:59:03.168
is studying the process of T cell exhaustion.

1014
00:59:03.908 --> 00:59:07.778
Many of you are likely familiar with this, but it's very important in oncology and

1015
00:59:07.848 --> 00:59:11.798
also in infectious diseases, and it's the concept that with T cells, which begin as

1016
00:59:11.828 --> 00:59:15.388
naive T cells, begin to expose an antigen, either through a

1017
00:59:15.428 --> 00:59:19.148
virus or for cancer cells. They transition through persistent

1018
00:59:19.208 --> 00:59:22.768
antigen exposure through different cell states to form this terminally

1019
00:59:22.788 --> 00:59:24.978
differentiated cell state known as exhaustion.

1020
00:59:25.828 --> 00:59:29.338
And this is really important because these T cells are alive, they're present, but

1021
00:59:29.348 --> 00:59:33.268
they're not functioning properly to eliminate the antigen-expressing cell

1022
00:59:33.288 --> 00:59:33.968
or virus.

1023
00:59:34.888 --> 00:59:37.988
And this was really interesting because it's been previously really well defined

1024
00:59:38.028 --> 00:59:41.608
that each of these different transitional states from a naive to exhausted T

1025
00:59:41.628 --> 00:59:45.088
cells is characterized by very specific gene expression

1026
00:59:45.108 --> 00:59:49.088
programs, which are set up by specific transcription factors,

1027
00:59:49.108 --> 00:59:52.818
and there's specific chromatin states and DNA methylation states which are

1028
00:59:52.908 --> 00:59:55.408
unique to naive versus exhausted T cells.

1029
00:59:57.068 --> 01:00:00.118
And so many of you likely know this, but splicing largely happens

1030
01:00:00.148 --> 01:00:03.968
co-transcriptionally. So whenever there are situations where there's a unique

1031
01:00:03.988 --> 01:00:07.968
transcription factor state and chromatin state of a cell, there's often unique

1032
01:00:08.068 --> 01:00:12.048
RNA isoforms for that cell as well, and that's something that hadn't really

1033
01:00:12.068 --> 01:00:14.838
been well investigated, and certainly not in human cells.

1034
01:00:15.868 --> 01:00:19.508
So we had a very simple hypothesis to start with here, which is we hypothesized

1035
01:00:19.528 --> 01:00:23.388
that there would be alterations in splicing as key mediators of T cell

1036
01:00:23.448 --> 01:00:25.148
exhaustion in cancer.

1037
01:00:26.388 --> 01:00:30.168
To evaluate this, we started with patients with melanoma, where we sorted

1038
01:00:30.228 --> 01:00:33.828
out CD8 T cells from their tumors for patients with metastatic

1039
01:00:33.868 --> 01:00:37.538
melanoma, as well as their peripheral blood, and performed

1040
01:00:37.588 --> 01:00:41.258
single-cell long-read RNA seq of the CD8 T cells from these two different

1041
01:00:41.288 --> 01:00:45.248
compartments.And the goal here was just like conventional short-read

1042
01:00:45.328 --> 01:00:48.868
RNA-seq to capture the different T cell types based on their gene expression

1043
01:00:48.928 --> 01:00:52.788
characteristics, but hopefully now with the long-read to get closer to

1044
01:00:52.848 --> 01:00:56.388
full-length RNA isoforms unique to these different T cell states.

1045
01:00:57.248 --> 01:01:00.188
As it turns out, you can also use the long-read data to look at the clonality of

1046
01:01:00.208 --> 01:01:03.668
the T cells because you can capture their TCR alpha and beta chains.

1047
01:01:04.328 --> 01:01:08.288
And in really interesting data, which I won't get to talk about today, we can

1048
01:01:08.328 --> 01:01:12.188
now also start to resolve repetitive regions of the genome, which Megan alluded

1049
01:01:12.208 --> 01:01:15.048
to in her talk in melanoma cells earlier today.

1050
01:01:17.088 --> 01:01:21.038
So this is a UMAP of the four patients' blood and tumor T cells

1051
01:01:21.048 --> 01:01:24.808
from that prior slide, and they're colored based on their T cell state.

1052
01:01:24.888 --> 01:01:28.688
So the more purplish colors here are more exhausted T cell populations

1053
01:01:29.128 --> 01:01:32.628
and more green are memory-activated and cytotoxic T cells.

1054
01:01:33.568 --> 01:01:37.118
On the right here is a heat map of the marker genes used to define these different

1055
01:01:37.148 --> 01:01:40.908
T cell states, and this has been very well studied and published based on many

1056
01:01:40.948 --> 01:01:43.548
prior data sets of short-read RNA-seq data.

1057
01:01:44.908 --> 01:01:48.588
And if we look at the distribution within the blood or the tissues of where these

1058
01:01:48.628 --> 01:01:51.928
different T cells are located, we see that the purple

1059
01:01:52.388 --> 01:01:56.188
groups of the exhausted T cell populations are mostly enriched within the tumor,

1060
01:01:56.808 --> 01:01:59.948
whereas the non-exhausted T cells are mostly present in the blood.

1061
01:01:59.968 --> 01:02:03.308
And this is very well known because as T cells encounter

1062
01:02:03.368 --> 01:02:06.088
antigen within the tumor, they're more likely to be exhausted.

1063
01:02:06.128 --> 01:02:09.978
So there's an accumulation of exhausted T cells within the tumor tissue as

1064
01:02:10.008 --> 01:02:10.678
expected.

1065
01:02:11.888 --> 01:02:15.408
But what we wanted to really add now into this is, are there unique RNA

1066
01:02:15.488 --> 01:02:19.348
isoforms in the exhausted versus non-exhausted CD8 T

1067
01:02:19.408 --> 01:02:19.808
cells?

1068
01:02:21.028 --> 01:02:23.908
And so this is a volcano plot answering that question.

1069
01:02:24.008 --> 01:02:27.738
Every dot on this volcano plot is an RNA isoform, so it's

1070
01:02:27.768 --> 01:02:31.668
not a gene, but rather an isoform. And what we're looking at in purple

1071
01:02:31.708 --> 01:02:35.268
here is isoforms that are upregulated in the exhausted cells

1072
01:02:35.668 --> 01:02:39.568
versus those upregulated in non-exhausted CD8 T cell subsets.

1073
01:02:40.768 --> 01:02:43.988
And so there are a lot of interesting events here, many of which are previously

1074
01:02:43.998 --> 01:02:46.788
unannotated. They're not in reference databases for the

1075
01:02:46.808 --> 01:02:50.798
transcriptome and only resolve because of the long-read and the ability to look

1076
01:02:50.848 --> 01:02:54.778
at unique cell types, which are not really easily sequenced by bulk sequencing

1077
01:02:54.888 --> 01:02:55.268
efforts.

1078
01:02:56.128 --> 01:02:59.848
And you'll notice here that you'll see some gene names present on both sides of the

1079
01:02:59.888 --> 01:03:03.448
plot, and this represents genes that undergo an RNA isoform switching

1080
01:03:03.488 --> 01:03:07.028
event between exhausted and non-exhausted T cell state.

1081
01:03:08.788 --> 01:03:12.248
And so as we were looking at this data, we focused immediately on one gene in

1082
01:03:12.268 --> 01:03:15.508
particular because there's a very well role in T cell

1083
01:03:15.568 --> 01:03:19.528
exhaustion, and it's also a drug targeted melanoma, which is a

1084
01:03:19.568 --> 01:03:23.248
cell surface protein and immune checkpoint called LAG-3.

1085
01:03:23.398 --> 01:03:27.128
And you're seeing here two different isoforms of LAG-3, which are differentially

1086
01:03:27.188 --> 01:03:30.208
upregulated based on the state of the CD8 T cell.

1087
01:03:32.108 --> 01:03:35.548
So these are pseudo-bulk RNA sequencing coverage plots of

1088
01:03:35.608 --> 01:03:39.028
LAG-3 in the peripheral blood T cells, which are not

1089
01:03:39.068 --> 01:03:42.788
exhausted, versus the CD8 T cells in the tumor that are exhausted.

1090
01:03:43.548 --> 01:03:47.088
And what you're seeing here is there's a particular intron within LAG-3, which

1091
01:03:47.188 --> 01:03:51.128
actually has intron retention very prominently in non-exhausted

1092
01:03:51.188 --> 01:03:54.728
CD8 T cells, but in exhausted cells is very efficiently

1093
01:03:54.768 --> 01:03:58.708
removed. And if you look on the left here, this is the gene expression of the

1094
01:03:58.788 --> 01:04:00.528
parent gene in these different

1095
01:04:01.388 --> 01:04:05.228
tissue sites, and you see the upregulation of LAG-3 expression within the

1096
01:04:05.268 --> 01:04:05.608
tumor.

1097
01:04:06.948 --> 01:04:10.488
If we look at this in those more refined cell states from the single-cell data,

1098
01:04:10.948 --> 01:04:14.908
you see once again, as you go from memory activated in cytotoxic T cells to the

1099
01:04:14.968 --> 01:04:18.828
more exhausted cells, you see more and more efficient removal of this

1100
01:04:18.908 --> 01:04:19.448
intron.

1101
01:04:20.408 --> 01:04:24.068
And it turns out this intron is very important because it contains an in-frame

1102
01:04:24.148 --> 01:04:27.648
stop codon within it. And so the idea here is that this

1103
01:04:27.728 --> 01:04:31.348
retention of this intron would somehow influence expression of LAG-3,

1104
01:04:31.748 --> 01:04:35.328
either through triggering some form of mRNA decay or

1105
01:04:35.408 --> 01:04:37.948
truncated the transcript and protein early on.

1106
01:04:38.768 --> 01:04:42.128
And I should emphasize here, if you look again in reference databases, you will not

1107
01:04:42.148 --> 01:04:45.188
see a normal isoform that contains this interim retention.

1108
01:04:45.228 --> 01:04:49.098
It's something that is unannotated, but it does exist in normal cell states, in

1109
01:04:49.108 --> 01:04:50.618
particular, T cells.

1110
01:04:51.768 --> 01:04:55.158
Furthermore, for reasons I can't explain to you, even in our own

1111
01:04:55.228 --> 01:04:59.148
short-read deep RNA sequencing data, we don't see this differential

1112
01:04:59.168 --> 01:05:02.608
splicing event. It's really only been seen now through the use of long-read

1113
01:05:02.648 --> 01:05:03.268
sequencing.

1114
01:05:04.708 --> 01:05:07.608
And so again, for those of you not familiar with this, LAG-3 is an important cell

1115
01:05:07.688 --> 01:05:11.488
surface protein and an immune checkpoint, and it restrains T cell

1116
01:05:11.508 --> 01:05:15.208
receptor signaling, and it is the target of FDA-approved

1117
01:05:15.328 --> 01:05:19.168
antibodies targeting LAG-3 in combination with PD-1 for

1118
01:05:19.228 --> 01:05:21.488
patients with metastatic melanoma.

1119
01:05:21.568 --> 01:05:25.127
So it's an important role in T cell function and a drug target.

1120
01:05:26.768 --> 01:05:30.648
And it turns out you can induce this change in LAG-3 splicing in normal

1121
01:05:30.688 --> 01:05:34.178
T cells from normal donors. So if you take T cells from a normal donor and

1122
01:05:34.248 --> 01:05:37.488
acutely activate them versus chronically stimulate them,

1123
01:05:38.228 --> 01:05:42.088
chronic stimulation upregulates LAG-3 protein on the cell surface as well as

1124
01:05:42.108 --> 01:05:45.828
PD-1. And if you do the single-cell long-read in the

1125
01:05:45.868 --> 01:05:49.468
same CD8 T cells, you see very prominently again here the intron

1126
01:05:49.528 --> 01:05:53.468
retention event in the acute CD8 T cells, whereas the intron is

1127
01:05:53.488 --> 01:05:57.278
very efficiently removed again upon chronic stimulation of T cells.

1128
01:05:57.748 --> 01:06:01.248
And again, this correlates very beautifully with the level of LAG-3 mRNA

1129
01:06:01.288 --> 01:06:01.868
expression.

1130
01:06:03.838 --> 01:06:07.478
So the idea here is that there's an intron which is differentially excised based on

1131
01:06:07.508 --> 01:06:11.038
the state of the T cell. Exhausted T cells efficiently remove

1132
01:06:11.128 --> 01:06:14.458
this and give rise to the full-length protein coding form of LAG-3,

1133
01:06:14.988 --> 01:06:18.728
whereas acutely stimulated T cells actually have the intron retention event

1134
01:06:18.808 --> 01:06:21.868
normally under normal physiologic conditions.

1135
01:06:21.888 --> 01:06:24.748
And there's two possibilities here that are consequences of this.

1136
01:06:25.108 --> 01:06:28.408
The first is that this could trigger NMD, which as I'll show you, is actually

1137
01:06:28.508 --> 01:06:32.318
what's happening. But the other possibility before testing this formally is that

1138
01:06:32.368 --> 01:06:35.768
this could truncate the transcript and maybe even give rise to a truncated

1139
01:06:35.828 --> 01:06:39.568
LAG-3. The transmembrane domain is far more distal, so this would

1140
01:06:39.668 --> 01:06:41.728
still not be present on the cell surface.

1141
01:06:43.528 --> 01:06:47.348
So to try to evaluate this functionally, we created a minigene, so it's the entire

1142
01:06:47.388 --> 01:06:51.308
LAG-3 cDNA, but now contains this differential intron within

1143
01:06:51.368 --> 01:06:55.292
it.And so if you put an intronless LAG3 in cells, you see, of

1144
01:06:55.332 --> 01:06:58.632
course, only this short band here, which is the fully spliced form.

1145
01:06:59.432 --> 01:07:02.472
Wild type intron four, you have the spliced and unspliced.

1146
01:07:02.482 --> 01:07:05.872
And then as you create mutations within the intron, which force the intron

1147
01:07:05.912 --> 01:07:08.752
retention, now you have only this top band.

1148
01:07:08.772 --> 01:07:12.492
And in these same cells here, if you do a Western blot, you completely lose

1149
01:07:12.792 --> 01:07:13.911
LAG3 protein.

1150
01:07:15.692 --> 01:07:17.692
You can also see this by flow cytometry.

1151
01:07:17.792 --> 01:07:21.632
So we created a reporter now, which is again this LAG3 with the intron,

1152
01:07:21.772 --> 01:07:25.632
and then downstream is a GFP. And the idea here is that removal of this

1153
01:07:25.752 --> 01:07:29.612
intron would trigger LAG3 protein production as well as GFP,

1154
01:07:30.072 --> 01:07:33.712
but retention of this intron would block both proteins from being produced.

1155
01:07:34.532 --> 01:07:38.432
And so if you put these into cells, again, this will express LAG3 on the

1156
01:07:38.452 --> 01:07:42.332
cell surface as well as GFP. But as you force intron retention,

1157
01:07:42.372 --> 01:07:46.202
if you look down here, you completely lose surface LAG3 as well as

1158
01:07:46.252 --> 01:07:47.332
GFP production.

1159
01:07:48.452 --> 01:07:51.532
And so this was useful for us. We created a reporter from this and did CRISPR

1160
01:07:51.572 --> 01:07:55.312
screens to figure out regulators of LAG3 splicing, which I won't tell you

1161
01:07:55.352 --> 01:07:56.552
about further for now.

1162
01:07:57.592 --> 01:08:01.512
So what we've learned, as I've shown you so far, is that T cell exhaustion is

1163
01:08:01.632 --> 01:08:04.432
associated with a specific gene expression program.

1164
01:08:04.472 --> 01:08:06.112
It's very well studied previously.

1165
01:08:06.672 --> 01:08:09.492
But it's also associated with a specific RNA splicing

1166
01:08:10.332 --> 01:08:14.092
set of genes which are spliced characteristically in exhausted cells, one of

1167
01:08:14.132 --> 01:08:17.972
which is the splicing event in LAG3, which is important in T cell

1168
01:08:17.992 --> 01:08:21.913
function. We use this to create this reporter, and as we were doing

1169
01:08:21.932 --> 01:08:25.532
this work, we thought, instead of just using this splicing event to regulate

1170
01:08:25.652 --> 01:08:29.512
GFP, could we harness this splicing event to regulate gene expression

1171
01:08:29.732 --> 01:08:33.713
upon T cell exhaustion for some kind of therapeutic use?

1172
01:08:34.152 --> 01:08:38.032
And so the idea here was to use the splicing event in LAG3 to

1173
01:08:38.072 --> 01:08:40.972
differentially regulate some downstream gene of interest.

1174
01:08:41.463 --> 01:08:45.112
And so as we were thinking about this idea, several papers came out

1175
01:08:45.213 --> 01:08:48.972
describing that overexpression of a transcription factor called FOXO1

1176
01:08:49.452 --> 01:08:53.442
could mitigate T cell exhaustion in normal T cells and CAR T cells and

1177
01:08:53.552 --> 01:08:54.552
TCR T cells.

1178
01:08:55.492 --> 01:08:59.072
And so our thought was to try to use this splicing event now, just as LAG3 is

1179
01:08:59.112 --> 01:09:03.111
regulated in the cell upon exhaustion, use this to regulate a downstream

1180
01:09:03.132 --> 01:09:03.892
gene of interest.

1181
01:09:05.293 --> 01:09:07.152
And so this turns out to work very well.

1182
01:09:07.192 --> 01:09:10.972
So we have a mini gene now, which is just exon four to five of

1183
01:09:11.032 --> 01:09:13.612
LAG3, no other part of its coding sequence.

1184
01:09:14.293 --> 01:09:17.772
And then downstream is a P2A and the FOXO1 cDNA.

1185
01:09:18.452 --> 01:09:21.932
And we put these into T cells and look what happens to FOXO1 expression

1186
01:09:22.272 --> 01:09:25.253
upon acute versus chronic stimulation of the T cells.

1187
01:09:26.312 --> 01:09:30.092
As a positive control, we have constitutive overexpression of FOXO1, and a negative

1188
01:09:30.152 --> 01:09:32.293
control is a mini gene with no payload.

1189
01:09:33.722 --> 01:09:37.472
And so as you stimulate these T cells, you can do intracellular flow cytometry to

1190
01:09:37.512 --> 01:09:40.492
look at FOXO1 protein. In the acute setting,

1191
01:09:41.112 --> 01:09:44.512
FOXO1 is only upregulated in the positive control group, as

1192
01:09:44.552 --> 01:09:48.472
expected. But as T cells become chronically stimulated, now we

1193
01:09:48.512 --> 01:09:51.352
see the FOXO1 expression shifting to be upregulated

1194
01:09:51.652 --> 01:09:54.512
conditionally in the chronically stimulated T cells.

1195
01:09:56.512 --> 01:10:00.452
And it turns out that not only are we regulating FOXO1 expression, but

1196
01:10:00.532 --> 01:10:03.882
just as previously been published that FOXO1 mitigates exhaustion,

1197
01:10:04.792 --> 01:10:08.732
in the conditional LAG3 FOXO1 circuit, we

1198
01:10:08.752 --> 01:10:12.522
see downregulation of other immune checkpoints, LAG3, PD1,

1199
01:10:12.672 --> 01:10:15.772
TIM3, and the transcription factor Talks, and coordinate

1200
01:10:15.832 --> 01:10:19.651
upregulation of cytotoxic proteins like granzyme B and perforin.

1201
01:10:20.172 --> 01:10:24.102
So this splicing regulated payload of FOXO1 seems to be doing

1202
01:10:24.172 --> 01:10:27.372
something positive compared to just the constitutive overexpression.

1203
01:10:28.592 --> 01:10:31.432
So those are just in T cells that have not been engineered otherwise.

1204
01:10:32.012 --> 01:10:35.032
And I thought the best way to really to test this would be to put this into an

1205
01:10:35.112 --> 01:10:38.332
anti-tumor T cell, like a CAR or TCR T cell.

1206
01:10:39.192 --> 01:10:41.292
So I'll show you the last few experiments here where we did this.

1207
01:10:41.332 --> 01:10:45.172
So this is a T cell that has a TCR that recognizes a cancer testis

1208
01:10:45.192 --> 01:10:48.961
antigen, NY-ESO-1, commonly expressed in melanoma and

1209
01:10:49.012 --> 01:10:50.552
many other forms of cancer.

1210
01:10:51.432 --> 01:10:55.302
And then additionally, we've put in either FOXO1 as a positive control or

1211
01:10:55.352 --> 01:10:57.532
this splicing regulated form of FOXO1.

1212
01:10:58.452 --> 01:11:01.952
And we looked to see what happens to the tumor cells and T cells upon

1213
01:11:02.112 --> 01:11:05.852
repeated rechallenge of the T cells with tumor every 48

1214
01:11:05.932 --> 01:11:06.332
hours.

1215
01:11:07.652 --> 01:11:11.312
And so this is a graph now of the tumor growth over time in this

1216
01:11:11.352 --> 01:11:14.972
experiment, and the arrows here show the rechallenge happening every 48

1217
01:11:15.052 --> 01:11:15.532
hours.

1218
01:11:16.352 --> 01:11:19.512
In gray here is the tumor growth without T cells.

1219
01:11:19.612 --> 01:11:22.312
You can see the tumor cells grow unchecked as expected.

1220
01:11:23.232 --> 01:11:26.672
In blue are the TCR T cells against the tumor, which have an

1221
01:11:26.732 --> 01:11:30.592
anti-tumor activity as expected. And then the red is a positive control.

1222
01:11:30.652 --> 01:11:34.512
So FOXO1 overexpression promotes anti-tumor activity of the T cells

1223
01:11:34.892 --> 01:11:38.432
as previously been published. But you'll notice here in the yellow, this is the

1224
01:11:38.492 --> 01:11:42.231
splicing regulated FOXO1. As these T cells encounter repeated challenge,

1225
01:11:42.662 --> 01:11:46.652
now we see a separation of the curve, suggesting that there's some effect

1226
01:11:46.712 --> 01:11:50.412
now of temporally regulating this payload expression upon

1227
01:11:50.452 --> 01:11:51.712
tumor repeated challenge.

1228
01:11:53.652 --> 01:11:57.152
We've also done this in vivo, where we introduced the tumor cells in vivo and the T

1229
01:11:57.252 --> 01:12:00.732
cells, and once again, if you just focus on the yellow group here, the greatest

1230
01:12:00.792 --> 01:12:04.572
anti-tumor activity is in the splicing regulated FOXO1

1231
01:12:04.612 --> 01:12:05.212
expression.

1232
01:12:06.692 --> 01:12:10.072
And what I want to emphasize with this system is that we're not limited to

1233
01:12:10.092 --> 01:12:13.532
FOXO1. Anything you can clone into this vector can be temporally

1234
01:12:13.552 --> 01:12:17.272
regulated in this manner. And so just as one example, we

1235
01:12:17.532 --> 01:12:20.622
thought about other things that could be useful to regulate in this way, and one

1236
01:12:20.672 --> 01:12:24.572
idea is a cytokine, IL-12. This is a cytokine that's

1237
01:12:24.632 --> 01:12:27.912
well known to have anti-cancer properties, but if delivered

1238
01:12:27.952 --> 01:12:30.412
systemically, it also has great toxicity.

1239
01:12:30.512 --> 01:12:33.672
So there's been a great effort to try to develop local or temporal

1240
01:12:33.752 --> 01:12:35.972
delivery an expression of IL-12.

1241
01:12:36.812 --> 01:12:40.302
So the idea here is that this is now expressed downstream of the splicing

1242
01:12:40.432 --> 01:12:44.372
regulated switch to turn on and off IL-12 upon the state

1243
01:12:44.452 --> 01:12:48.352
of T cell stimulation. So the chronically stimulated cells

1244
01:12:48.432 --> 01:12:51.052
uniquely remove the intron to drive the IL-12

1245
01:12:51.112 --> 01:12:54.532
expression.And so just to show you that this is flow

1246
01:12:54.612 --> 01:12:58.592
cytometry now on the y-axis, looking at IL-12 in negative

1247
01:12:58.632 --> 01:13:01.262
control for splicing regulated IL-12.

1248
01:13:01.332 --> 01:13:05.032
So upon chronic T cell stimulation, IL-12 is now being

1249
01:13:05.072 --> 01:13:05.602
produced.

1250
01:13:06.592 --> 01:13:10.462
And it's well known that as IL-12 is produced, it also leads the T cells to

1251
01:13:10.512 --> 01:13:14.292
secrete interferon gamma. And so you can see here the interferon gamma production

1252
01:13:14.372 --> 01:13:18.292
very much mirrors that of IL-12. So this is a way to temporally

1253
01:13:18.432 --> 01:13:21.812
regulate a cytokine's expression upon chronic T cell

1254
01:13:21.872 --> 01:13:22.552
stimulation.

1255
01:13:24.632 --> 01:13:27.712
So to summarize, what I've presented to you all today is that it's very well

1256
01:13:27.792 --> 01:13:31.232
studied that T cell exhaustion is associated with a specific gene

1257
01:13:31.292 --> 01:13:34.232
expression program and epigenetic state.

1258
01:13:35.112 --> 01:13:38.432
But we've also now identified this is associated with a very unique RNA

1259
01:13:38.512 --> 01:13:42.112
isoform landscape of expression as well.

1260
01:13:42.172 --> 01:13:45.652
One of which splicing events are highlighted with this splicing event in LAG3,

1261
01:13:45.832 --> 01:13:49.412
which is previously undescribed and unannotated, but is very important in

1262
01:13:49.452 --> 01:13:52.852
regulating, physiologically, LAG3 transmembrane protein

1263
01:13:52.912 --> 01:13:56.292
expression in T cells. And so we identified that

1264
01:13:56.512 --> 01:13:56.982
acutely

1265
01:13:57.851 --> 01:14:01.722
activated T cells have this intron-retained form of LAG3, preventing the protein

1266
01:14:01.722 --> 01:14:05.342
from being expressed. But as T cells are chronically activated and

1267
01:14:05.372 --> 01:14:08.822
exhausted, this intron is efficiently removed,

1268
01:14:09.252 --> 01:14:13.152
providing LAG3 protein to be translated in those cells.

1269
01:14:14.312 --> 01:14:18.272
We then utilize this event now to temporarily regulate gene expression, just as

1270
01:14:18.352 --> 01:14:21.932
LAG3 itself is regulated in these cells, looking at therapeutic

1271
01:14:21.972 --> 01:14:25.112
payloads including FOXL1 and IL-12.

1272
01:14:26.732 --> 01:14:30.712
